TY  - JOUR
AU  - Docgne, Sandrine
AU  - Duarte, Diogo
T1  - Price Uncertainty and Debt Covenants: Evidence from U.S. Oil Producers
PY  - 2024
Y1  - 2024/08/01
DO  - 10.1093/rcfs/cfac033
JO  - The Review of Corporate Finance Studies
JA  - Review of Corporate Finance Studies
VL  - 13
IS  - 3
SP  - 712
EP  - 738
SN  - 2046-9128
AB  - We use an exogenous, forward-looking measure of price uncertainty to examine the effect of uncertainty on the use of covenants in private and public debt contracts. The effect of uncertainty differs significantly in loans versus bonds, suggesting that private and public lenders face different incentives when contracting under high uncertainty. In loans, uncertainty increases the use of performance-based covenants. In contrast, covenant usage decreases in bonds, but firms with low agency conflicts mainly drive this effect. However, bondholders require higher spreads to offset the lack of protection with fewer covenants. Hedging does not affect the covenant-uncertainty relationship for debt contracts. (JEL: G21, G23, G32, D82, D81)
Y2  - 4/24/2026
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rcfs/cfac033
ER  - 




